Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text:
The Property’s prime location offers substantial commuting options with the IND Eighth Avenue Line servicing the A, C and E subway lines on the block, footsteps from the building’s entrance.

There are multiple bus lines that cross cut 49th Street and 8th Avenue and provide access throughout the borough, including the M20, M50 and M104. Additionally, the Port Authority Bus Terminal, a major regional transportation hub, is a few blocks South of the Property.

304 West 49th Street presents a tremendous opportunity for a developer or owner-user to acquire a vacant building and reconstruct it to a diverse set of uses in one of Manhattan’s most well established sub markets.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
CBRE HAS BEEN RETAINED ON AN EXCLUSIVE BASIS to sell 304 West 49th Street (the Property), an existing parking garage with air rights that can be redeveloped for an array of highly valuable uses. Directly facing the internationally acclaimed Worldwide Plaza at the center of Midtown West, the Property is ideally situated to take advantage of its A plus location.

304 West 49th Street currently contains a 50’ wide, 6-story building measuring 28,245 sq. ft. and has an additional 7,404 sq. ft. of unused air rights.The Property, which can be delivered vacant, is split zoned with half of the lot lying in a C6-4 high density mixed-use zoning district and the other half of the lot positioned in an R8 residential zoning district. The total combined buildable square footage is 35,649 sq. ft. and the site can be developed or converted to several uses including residential, mixed-use, hotel and community facility.

Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text:
Situated near I-86 just outside of Jamestown, the property is within a few hours drive of Buffalo, Erie, Pittsburgh, and Cleveland.

Falconer is part of the greater Jamestown area, the largest population center in Chautauqua County, and is located near the eastern end of Chautauqua Lake. Approximately 86,000 people are within a 30-minute drive of the property drawing workers from Chautauqua and Cattaraugus County in New York, as well northern Pennsylvania.

The Jamestown area has a long history of manufacturing from early craftsmen building furniture and tools. Today nearly 20 percent of the county’s workforce is employed in manufacturing at firms such as Bush Industries, Cummins Inc., Jamestown Container Cos., Monofrax LLC, Fancher Chair Co., Weber Knapp Co., Blackstone Advanced Technologies LLC, Dawson Metal Co., Artone LLC, Dahlstrom Roll Form, TitanX Engine Cooling Inc., Colecraft Commercial Furnishings, Rand Machine, SKF USA Inc., and Jamestown Plastics.
